**Implementation**

```ts
/**
 * Debounce a function.
 *
 * @param fn      Function to debounce. Its `this` value and arguments are preserved.
 * @param ms      Number of milliseconds to wait before invoking the trailing edge.
 * @param opts    Optional configuration.
 *                • leading – if true, the first call is executed immediately; further
 *                calls inside the wait window are ignored. No trailing call is made.
 *
 * @returns A debounced version of `fn` with an extra `cancel()` method.
 *
 * The returned function has exactly the same call‑signature as `fn`
 * (thanks to the generic `T`) and a `cancel` method that clears any
 * pending invocation.
 */
function debounce<
  T extends (...args: any[]) => void
>(
  fn: T,
  ms: number,
  opts: { leading?: boolean } = {}
): T & { cancel(): void } {
  // ----- internal state -------------------------------------------------
  let timerId: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | null = null;
  // stored arguments for the *trailing* edge (used only when !leading)
  let lastArgs: Parameters<T> | null = null;
  // stored `this` for the trailing edge
  let lastThis: any = null;

  const { leading = false } = opts;

  // ----- helper that actually invokes `fn` -------------------------------
  const invoke = () => {
    if (lastArgs) {
      fn.apply(lastThis, lastArgs);
      lastArgs = null;
      lastThis = null;
    }
  };

  // ----- the debounced wrapper -----------------------------------------
  const debounced = function (this: any, ...args: Parameters<T>) {
    if (leading) {
      // ---- leading‑edge mode -------------------------------------------
      if (timerId === null) {
        // first call in the window → fire immediately
        fn.apply(this, args);
        // start a timer that only blocks further calls
        timerId = setTimeout(() => {
          timerId = null; // window ended, allow a new leading call
        }, ms);
      }
      // else: we are inside the blocking window → ignore the call
    } else {
      // ---- trailing‑edge mode ------------------------------------------
      // remember the latest call
      lastArgs = args as Parameters<T>;
      lastThis = this;

      // reset the timer
      if (timerId !== null) clearTimeout(timerId);
      timerId = setTimeout(() => {
        timerId = null;
        invoke(); // run once after the wait period
      }, ms);
    }
  } as T & { cancel(): void };

  // ----- cancel method --------------------------------------------------
  debounced.cancel = () => {
    if (timerId !== null) {
      clearTimeout(timerId);
      timerId = null;
    }
    lastArgs = null;
    lastThis = null;
  };

  return debounced;
}
```

### How it works

| Mode | First call | Calls while timer is active | Call after timer expires |
|------|------------|-----------------------------|--------------------------|
| **trailing (default)** | Nothing happens immediately | Arguments/`this` are stored, timer is reset each time | The *last* stored call is invoked |
| **leading (`{leading:true}`)** | `fn` is called instantly | All subsequent calls are ignored until `ms` elapse | Nothing happens (no trailing call) |

* The timer is created with `setTimeout` and cleared with `clearTimeout`.  
* The generic `T` guarantees the returned wrapper has exactly the same signature as the original function, preserving both argument types and the `void` return type.  
* `this` is preserved by using `fn.apply(this, args)` (or the stored `lastThis`).  
* `debounced.cancel()` clears any pending timer and forgets saved arguments, so no later invocation will occur.  

No external libraries are required; the implementation works in both browser and Node environments.

